source_code.code:
void foo (){
   f( g );    //implicitly instantiates f with T=int, U= char and calls it.
}

Bug.WithStack:
The symbol table does not currently handle the following:
void f( int ( *pf ) ( char ) );
int g( char );

void foo(){
   f( g );
}

The symbol table needs to compare two functions and determine if they have the 
same return type & parameters.  It also needs to support the function-to-
pointer conversion.

This will need to be supported before the table can handle the following:
template < class T, class U > void f( T(*)( T, U ) );
int g( int, char );
void foo (){
   f( g );    //implicitly instantiates f with T=int, U= char and calls it.
}
fixed in new DOM AST

Bug.WithOutStack:
The symbol table does not currently handle the following:
void f( int ( *pf ) ( char ) );
int g( char );

void foo(){
   f( g );
}

The symbol table needs to compare two functions and determine if they have the 
same return type & parameters.  It also needs to support the function-to-
pointer conversion.

This will need to be supported before the table can handle the following:
template < class T, class U > void f( T(*)( T, U ) );
int g( int, char );
void foo (){
   f( g );    //implicitly instantiates f with T=int, U= char and calls it.
}
fixed in new DOM AST

